"1522":"1522","about 1514":"about 1514","1475":"1475","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","of Stokenam, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Sherford, Devon, England, UK":"Sherford, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   March  ."],"variants":[{"name":"March","meanings":["English: habitational name from March (Cambridgeshire) or from any of numerous minor English placenames deriving from Middle English <i>marche</i> ‘boundary’ (partly from Old English <i>mearc</i> in the dative-case form <i>mearce</i>, partly from Old French <i>marche</i>). Compare   Mark   2.","Catalan: from the personal name <i>March</i>, Catalan equivalent of   Mark   1. This surname is also found in southern France.","German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>march</i>, Middle High German <i>marc(h)</i> ‘mark, sign, boundary’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word (Bavaria)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Marche was born in 1500, in Sherford, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Marche, was 25 and his mother, Marche, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Marche."},"et":{"1500–":"1500–Surnud","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1522–1550":"1522–1550","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1514–1583":"1514–1583","1475–Male":"1475–Surnud","1475–Female":"1475–Surnud","1514":"1514","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","about 1514":"umbes 1514","1475":"1475","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","of Stokenam, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sherford, Devon, England, UK":"Sherford, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1500–":"1500–Kuollut","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1522–1550":"1522–1550","1500–Female":"1500–Kuollut","1514–1583":"1514–1583","1475–Male":"1475–Kuollut","1475–Female":"1475–Kuollut","1514":"1514","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","about 1514":"noin 1514","1475":"1475","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","of Stokenam, Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sherford, Devon, England, UK":"Sherford, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1500–":"1500–Décédé","1500–Male":"1500–Décédé","1522–1550":"1522–1550","1500–Female":"1500–Décédée","1514–1583":"1514–1583","1475–Male":"1475–Décédé","1475–Female":"1475–Décédée","1514":"1514","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","about 1514":"environ 1514","1475":"1475","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","of Sto